[1]
Date: Sun 5 Feb 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: News web India, 5 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://news.webindia123.com/news/showdetails.asp?id=240786>

600 bird carcasses found in Ladakh, bird flu spread ruled out
-----------------------------------------------
About 600 carcasses of migratory birds, blamed for the spread of bird
flu in several countries across the globe, were found near the
Pangong Lake in the Ladakh region of Jammu and Kashmir some weeks
ago, sources said today [5 Feb 2006].
They said the dead birds were found near the Lake, which lies in the
northeast of Leh, in December last year [2005].
The sources said the birds could have possibly died of H5N1 avian
influenza (commonly known as bird flu).
However, the sources ruled out spread of the bird flu or any disease,
as there is no population around the famous blue brackish lake, half
of which runs to the other side of the India-China border.
The black-necked Siberian crane could be found around the Mahe
marshes, which are the only breeding ground for the migratory birds
in the lake.
The sources said one bird death was reported from Hokursar bird
sanctuary near here. The carcass has been sent to the High Security
Laboratory at Bhopal in Madhya Pradesh, which has a facility for
diagnosis of bird flu.
Talking to UNI, Deputy Director of the state Animal Husbandry
Department, Dr. Farooq Ahmed Kaloo, said there have been no reports
of the H5N1 virus in poultry or migratory birds in Jammu and Kashmir.
He said Jammu and Kashmir have unique protection from any such
disease carried by migratory birds.
"The state has natural filtration in the form of [the] mighty
Himalayas against diseases which are carried by migratory birds. Any
vector (affected bird) with compromised immunity gets killed on the
way," Dr. Kaloo added.
