Date: Sun 5 Feb 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: New Kerala.com, 5 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.newkerala.com/news2.php?action=fullnews&id=2950>

Toxic Yamuna water killed 47 birds
---------------------------------------
A day after 47 carcasses of migratory birds were found in the Indian
capital, experts said they believed the birds had died due to toxic
elements in the waters of the Yamuna river and not because of bird flu.
"We conducted post mortem examination on 3 birds at the Okhla Bird
Sanctuary, and we found the deaths were due to toxic water and not
flu," said Pragya Paromita Baruah, program officer with Wildlife
Trust of India (WTI).
"But we don't want to take any chances and have therefore sent the
carcasses for further tests," said Pragya.
WTI has sent one bird carcass to the animal disease laboratory at
Bhopal in Madhya Pradesh and 2 to the Indian Veterinary Research
Institute for tests.
WTI officials had found 47 dead birds, all of them migratory species,
at Okhla Bird Sanctuary Saturday [4 Feb 2006]. They also found at
least 6 dead fish, which too have been sent for tests.
The fact that all the dead birds were migratory species and not local
ones has led experts to believe they died after drinking the highly
polluted waters of the Yamuna.
"It seems that the birds in the Okhla Bird Sanctuary have become
accustomed to drinking poor quality water, and the migratory birds
died because of that," Pragya said.
Sanjeev Baruah, assistant program officer with WTI, said the dead
fish seemed to have died because of the toxic water, and we have also
sent the fish for tests."
During the post mortem of the 3 birds, small fish were found within
their stomachs, he said.
Pragya said the dead birds were found floating in the water by some
people who were taking a walk in the area Saturday [4 Feb 2006]. They
informed the authorities of the bird sanctuary.
"We found the carcasses of birds like the shoveller duck, little
egret, little cormorant, common teal, brown headed gull and black
headed gull in the area," Sanjeev said.
Pragya noted that WTI officials had found dead fish in the area
several times in the past. Information about the dead fish was given
to the authorities who had taken no action on it, she claimed.
