Source: AP via Free New Mexican, 5 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.freenewmexican.com/news/39048.html>

Nigeria testing birds found dead in north
-----------------------------------------------
Authorities are testing birds that mysteriously died in northern
Nigeria and called on poultry farmers to report cases of sickened
fowl, officials said on Sunday [5 Feb 2006].

Samples from birds that died in northern Kano State "in an outbreak
of a strange poultry disease" were sent for testing to 2 Nigerian
veterinary institutes, Agriculture Ministry official Salihu Jibrin
said, but did not say when results were expected.
He refused to speculate on whether the birds might have been infected
with bird flu, of which there have been no known cases in West
Africa. Health officials fear, however, the virus could enter
impoverished regions where many households raise chickens for
personal consumption.
"I lost 15 adult birds in one day," poultry farmer Abubakar Ibrahim
said in Kurnan Asabe, a village in Kano. "I initially noticed
restiveness among the birds before they started dying off one after the other."
Authorities urged farmers to monitor their flocks and report strange
ailments to authorities. "They are also advised to properly dispose
of dead birds in a hygienic manner to avoid further spread of the
disease," he said.
Kano state set up a committee of veterinary surgeons to visit farms
and watch out for evidence of a bird flu outbreak.
[Byline: Oloche Samuel]
